text:
Hey, Toufiq I think this query is more easy to read than the one which you showed in the video at @43:35.

--1. Fetch all staff who teach grade 8, 9, 10 and also fetch all the non-teaching staff (16 Records)
SELECT DISTINCT STF.STAFF_TYPE, (STF.FIRST_NAME||' '||STF.LAST_NAME) AS FULL_NAME, STF.AGE, STF.GENDER, 
	STF.JOIN_DATE
FROM STAFF AS STF 
JOIN CLASSES AS CLS ON STF.STAFF_ID = CLS.TEACHER_ID 
WHERE CLS.CLASS_NAME IN ('Grade 8','Grade 9','Grade 10')
UNION 
SELECT DISTINCT STF.STAFF_TYPE, (STF.FIRST_NAME||' '||STF.LAST_NAME) AS FULL_NAME, STF.AGE, STF.GENDER, STF.JOIN_DATE
FROM STAFF AS STF WHERE STAFF_TYPE = 'Non-Teaching'
ORDER BY STAFF_TYPE

--2. Fetch all staff who teach grade 8, 9, 10 and also fetch all the non-teaching staff (including duplicate results as well) (28 records)
SELECT  STF.STAFF_TYPE, (STF.FIRST_NAME||' '||STF.LAST_NAME) AS FULL_NAME, STF.AGE, STF.GENDER, 
	STF.JOIN_DATE
FROM STAFF AS STF 
JOIN CLASSES AS CLS ON STF.STAFF_ID = CLS.TEACHER_ID 
WHERE CLS.CLASS_NAME IN ('Grade 8','Grade 9','Grade 10')
UNION all
SELECT STF.STAFF_TYPE, (STF.FIRST_NAME||' '||STF.LAST_NAME) AS FULL_NAME, STF.AGE, STF.GENDER, STF.JOIN_DATE
FROM STAFF AS STF WHERE STAFF_TYPE = 'Non-Teaching'
ORDER BY STAFF_TYPE

SQL is an ANSI standard so the sql used in any rdbms is almost (90%) same but some of the rdbms may have created their own functions to perform certain task .. to_date works in oracle and Postgres but does not work in MySQL and MSSQL .. Similarly there would be some other functions too..

Generally the concepts and general syntax is common across all rdbms but some functions may be created specific to an rdbms ..

text:
Hi, do you mean  you want to practice SQL?
If so, then start by installing RDBMS (such as PostgreSQL, MySQL, Oracle, Microsoft SQL Server etc.) in your computer. 

If you wish to install PostgreSQL, then you can refer to my video on how to install and setup. Link here https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1aybOgni7lI&t=47s

Once RDBMS is installed, then create some dummy tables and insert data into it. 
Then practice writing different queries to fetch different data.
You can download some the sample tables, insert scripts and queries from my blog.
Link here https://techtfq.com/sql/sql-basics-tutorial-for-beginners
You can find 2 buttons "Download DDL & DML" & "Download SELECT Queries" to download the SQL scripts which you can use to get started with your learning.

Hope this helps.
author: techTFQ

text:
Hi, below query should work:

select a.* 
from (select * from employee
	   where designation = 'doctor') a
join (select * from employee 
 	   where designation = 'supervisor') b
	   on a.supervisor_employee_id = b.Employee_Id and a.rating > b.rating;
